{
  "text": "It is notable that further development of such systems was controversial. Although there has been an obvious interest in these ND formalisms as representing a 'natural' way of reasoning, ND systems were often considered as inappropriate for an algorithmic representation [CITATION_1] . This scepticism is not surprising because in general we can have in the proof formulae that violate the subformula property (often thought as crucial for automated deduction), which requires that in a proof, any formula which occurs in the conclusion of a rule, is a (negation of) subformula of its premises.",
